 a new virtual device (e.g., Pixel 4).\\n        *   Start the emulator.\\n        *   Install the **Expo Go app** on the emulator via its Play Store.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Step 2: Create Your New Expo Project\\n\\nNow, let's create your app!\\n\\n1.  **Open your Terminal or Command Prompt.**\\n\\n2.  **Create a new Expo project:**\\n    ```bash\\n    npx create-expo-app my-first-expo-app\\n    ```\\n    *   `npx` runs the `create-expo-app` command without globally installing it.\\n    *   `my-first-expo-app` is the name of your project. You can choose any name.\\n    *   You'll be asked to choose a template. For simplicity, select `blank` (a minimal app).\\n\\n3.  **Navigate into your new project directory:**\\n    ```bash\\n    cd my-first-expo-app\\n    ```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Step 3: Run Your App in Development Mode\\n\\n1.  **Start the Expo development server:**\\n    ```bash\\n    npm start\\n    # or\\n    yarn start\\n    ```\\n    This will open a new browser tab with Expo Developer Tools and display a QR code in your terminal.\\n\\n2.  **Open your app using Expo Go:**\\n\\n    *   **On a Physical Android Device:**\\n        1.  Open the **Expo Go app** on your Android device.\\n        2.  Tap on **\\\"Scan QR Code\\\"** (usually a camera icon) and scan the QR code displayed in your terminal or the Expo Developer Tools browser tab.\\n        3.  Your app should start loading on your device!\\n\\n    *   **On an Android Emulator:**\\n        1.  Make sure your emulator is running.\\n        2.  In your terminal (where `npm start` is running), press `a`. This will automatically try to open the app on the running Android emulator.\\n        3.  Alternatively, open the Expo Go app on the emulator and manually type the \\\"Network\\\" URL from your terminal into the \\\"Enter URL manually\\\" field.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Step 4: Develop Your App (Code Examples)\\n\\nNow that your app is running, let's make some changes!\\n\\n1.  **Open your project in VS Code:**\\n    ``